The Village Voice}{\fs24  (February 22, 2002).}}}{\fs24   What becomes of writing and publishing in such a climate?  As one example, consider that Barnes and Noble refused to carry Jonathan Tel\rquote s }{\i\fs24 Arafat\rquote s Elephant}{\fs24 
, a collection of short stories, unless the title was changed.  (Since Tel refused, of the big chains, only Borders is carrying the book.)  
\par At the same time, In the midst of all this\emdash from September 12 on\emdash has come a widespread circulation of poems by e-mail, appearances in newspapers and in memorials (both \'93official\'94
 and impromptu), with favorites including its own modernist canon of Moore, Yeats, Heaney, Auden.  Whose \'93modernism\'94 is this?  Whose poetics provides such epigrammatic comforts? 
\par There has been a clarion call for a new \'93accessibility\'94 in our poetry.  Among others, this item from the }{\i\fs24 CLMP Newswire}{\fs24  concerning New York City editors\rquote  responses to \'939-11\'94: Martha Rhodes of Four Way Books describes 
\'93looking more for the essential in language and accessibility.  For the leaner and meaner.\'94}{\fs24\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 
